\begin{abstract}
\textit{Abstract: In this study of quantitative reasoning in K-12 mathematics education within the United States (U.S.), researchers aimed to identify effective strategies for improving students' mathematical competencies, particularly focusing on algebra and statistics problems which are often cited as areas where American students typically underperform internationally. Methodologically, a mixed-methods approach was employed involving quantitative assessment of test scores before and after the implementation of targeted pedagogical interventions across multiple school districts with diverse socioeconomic backgrounds (n=120), as well as qualitative surveys to gauge student engagement. Key findings revealed that personalized learning environments significantly elevated students' performance in algebra, while collaborative problem-solving activities had a pronounced effect on statistics understanding. The study also highlighted the importance of continuous professional development for teachers and how it correlates positively with improved student outcomes (Pearson correlation coefficient r=0.65). Implications suggest that tailored educational strategies have substantial potential to mitigate disparities in math proficiency, thereby contributing constructive insights into the enhancement of U.S.'s international standing in mathematics education while also indicating a pathway for system-wide pedagogical improvements and teacher training programs aimed at nurturing mathematical competencies from an early age through high school graduation (Johnson et al., 2023).}

