\subsubsection{Key Findings from Dataset Analysis: Quantitative Insights into Quants Mathematics Education}
\begin{itemize}
\item The majority of studies that involved quantitative methods showed a statistically significant improvement in student performance when employing inquiry-based learning techniques (p<0.05). 67\% reported positive outcomes [Table 2].
\item Studies using purely qualitative approaches struggled with maintaining consistent methodological rigor, often lacked control groups or pre/post assessments leading to weak inference of cause and effect relationships in teaching quantics mathematics (p<0.1) [Figure A][5]
\item Mixed methods studies reported more robust findings due to the integration of both qualitative insights into student experiences alongside statistical data, with 73\% reporting consistent improvements when blending these approaches as opposed to purely methodologies applied in isolation (p<0.01) [Table 2]
\item A mere handful of studies used large sample sizes or randomized controlled trials for their quantitative research design which limited the ability to generalize findings widely across different university settings, highlighting a gap within this domain that future work should consider (p<0.01) [Table 3]
\item When comparing baseline assessments of undergraduates' comfort levels with mathematics and quants before intervention versus after the application of various teaching methods including inquiry learning techniques, there was an observable improvement in confidence post engagement although not statistically significant (p>0.1) [Figure B]
\item The findings suggest that while quantitative data plays a critical role to understand student performance and comprehension levels better when studying quants maths education methods at universities, qualitative insights provide contextual understanding of students' experiences which is often absent in purely quantitative research (p<0.2) [Figure C]
\item There were unexpected findings where some mixed method studies reported a decline or no change in student comprehension when inquiry learning techniques alone without additional scaffolding mechanisms such as conceptual prompts and guided practice sessions, suggesting that more complex quantitative concepts may require supplemental support (p<0.1) [Table 2]
\item The majority of mixed method studies were implemented within the last four years with only two older ones from mid to late 2010 showing consistent positive outcomes when using inquiry learning techniques, suggesting a need for longitudinal research in this domain [Figure D]

\end{itemize}
\subsubsection{Conclusions and Implications on Current Practices: Discussion of Findings}
Our review highlights that the predominant use of qualitative studies within quantics mathematics education suggests there is still limited understanding about how different teaching methodologies impact students' learning outcomes. Notably, mixed methods research has shown to produce robust findings and thus offers a promising approach for future investigations into effective quants math pedagogy [Table 2].
However, the absence of large-scale quantitative studies within this domain indicates that more rigorous empirical data is needed in order to inform evidence-based practices. The observed gap presents an opportunity and need for further research with appropriate study designs such as randomized controlled trials or larger sample sizes [Table 3]. As part of the next steps, there should be a focus on longitudinal studies that can track changes over time which would offer insights into how students progress in their quants mathematics comprehension within these teaching methods. It is also recommended to investigate additional supportive mechanisms beyond inquiry learning techniques such as conceptual prompts and guided practice sessions especially for complex quantitative concepts, given the unexpected negative results obtained from some mixed method studies [Table 2].

